The algebra is of infinite representation type. Over this algebra, we have a  Wakamatsu-tilting module of finite  type (and hence, a good Wakamatsu-tilting module)

\vskip 5pt
\centerline{$T={\footnotesize \begin{array}{c}   2\\ 1\end{array}} \oplus {\footnotesize \begin{array}{c} 1\ 3\\2 \end{array}} \oplus {\footnotesize \ 3\ } \oplus {\footnotesize \begin{array}{c} 4\\ 3\ 5 \end{array}}\oplus {\footnotesize \begin{array}{c} 5\\4 \end{array}} \oplus {\footnotesize \begin{array}{c} 6\\5 \end{array}} \oplus {\footnotesize \begin{array}{c} 7\\ 6\ 6 \end{array}} $.}



\vskip 5pt
Indeed, one can check that the subcategory ${{\mathrm{{KerExt}}}}\setcounter{equation}{0}_R^1(-,{_T{{\mathcal{{X}}}}\setcounter{equation}{0}})$ is of finite representation type, while the subcategory ${_T{{\mathcal{{X}}}}\setcounter{equation}{0}}$ is of infinite representation type.



































